4zp.title: Uncountability (Math 3)
4zp.clickbait: Formal definition of uncountability, and foundational considerations.
4zp.text:
A [-3jz] $X$ is *uncountable* if there is no [499 bijection] between $X$ and  [45h $\mathbb{N}$]. Equivalently, there is no [4b7 injection] from $X$ to $\mathbb{N}$.

## Foundational Considerations ##

In set theories without the [69b axiom of choice], such as [ZF Zermelo Frankel set theory] without choice (ZF), it can be [5km consistent] that there is a [-cardinal_number] $\kappa$ that is incomparable to $\aleph_0$. That is, there is no injection from $\kappa$ to $\aleph_0$ nor from $\aleph_0$ to $\kappa$. In this case, cardinality is not a [540 total order], so it doesn't make sense to think of uncountability as "larger" than $\aleph_0$. In the presence of choice, [5sh cardinality is a linear order], so an uncountable set can be thought of as "larger" than a countable set.

Countability in one [-model] is not necessarily countability in another. By [skolems_paradox Skolem's Paradox], there is a model of set theory $M$ where its [6gl power set] of the naturals, denoted $2^\mathbb N_M \in M$ is countable when considered outside the model. Of course, it is a [6fk theorem] that $2^\mathbb N _M$ is uncountable, but that is within the model. That is, there is a bijection $f : \mathbb N \to 2^\mathbb N_M$ that is not inside the model $M$ (when $f$ is considered as a set, its graph), and there is no such bijection inside $M$. This means that (un)countability is not [absoluteness absolute].
